        <fields>
            <name>Header_Text_0_0_0</name>
            <fieldText>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;font-size: 16px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Home Office Circular – Rehabilitation of Offenders Act&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rehabilitation of Offenders Act&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;As you wish to be considered for a position which is exempt from the Rehabilitation of Offenders Act 1974 you may be subject to a Disclosure Barring Service check.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Blue Arrow is bound by the DBS Code of Practice and has policies for both the Recruitment of Ex- Offenders and the Storage and Disposal of DBS checks, copies of which are available upon request.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Having a criminal conviction will not necessarily bar you from working for Blue Arrow.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Under the Rehabilitation of Offenders Act 1974 (Exceptions) Order 1975, applicants for certain positions bringing them into contact with vulnerable persons are not entitled to withhold information about convictions which for other purposes are “spent”. In such a situation workers are expected to provide Blue Arrow with a full statement of any criminal convictions, police investigations or cautions and written permission to disclose this information to clients.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;FURTHER INFORMATION REGARDING CONVICTION INFORMATION&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;On 29 May 2013, legislation came into force that allows certain old and minor cautions and convictions to no longer be subject to disclosure.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;In addition, employers will no longer be able to take an individual’s old and minor cautions into account when making decisions.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;All cautions and convictions for specified serious violent and sexual offences, and other specified offences of relevance for posts concerned with safeguarding children and vulnerable adults, will remain subject to disclosure. In addition, all convictions resulting in a custodial sentence, whether or not suspended, will remain subject to disclosure, as will all convictions where an individual has more than one conviction recorded.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Full details on the filtering of old and minor cautions and convictions can be found on the DBS website as follows: &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dbs-filtering-guidance&quot; rel=&quot;noopener noreferrer&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;www.gov.uk/government/collections/dbs-filtering-guidance&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</fieldText>
            <fieldType>DisplayText</fieldType>
        </fields>
